	author = "M. Deveaux and B. Arnoldi-Meadows and G. Bertolone and G. Claus and A. Dorokhov and M. Goffe and A. Himmi and K. Jaaskelainen and P. Klaus and M. Koziel and F. Marx and F. Morel and C. Müntz and H. Pham and M. Specht and I. Valin and J. Stroth and M. Winter",
	keywords = "CPS, MAPS, Vertex Detector, Compressed Baryonic Matter experiment",
%%	abstract = "The Micro Vertex Detector (MVD) of the future Compressed Baryonic Matter (CBM) experiment at FAIR will have to provide a spatial precision of $\sim$ \SI{5}{\micro\meter} in combination with a material budget of 0.3% -- 0.5% X0 for a full detector station. Simultaneously, it will have to handle the rate and radiation load of operating the fixed target experiment at an average collision rate of \SI{100}{\kilo\hertz} (4--10 AGeV Au+Au collisions) or 10 MHz (up to 28 GeV p--A collisions). The harsh requirements call for a dedicated detector technology, which is the next generation CMOS Monolithic Active Pixel Sensor MIMOSIS. We report about the requirements for the sensor, introduce the design approach being followed to cope with it and show first test results from a first sensor prototype called MIMOSIS-0 ."
